The Video DAC is a chip – VDC-NUS, DENC-NUS, AVDC-NUS, or MAV-NUS depending on mainboard revision – that converts the 7-bit-wide synchronous [[Video Interface]] output to analog video.

Early revisions (VDC-NUS) use an external encoder (ENC-NUS) to generate composite and S-Video. Later revisions (DENC-NUS, AVDC-NUS, MAV-NUS) integrate this functionality. A variant using S-RGB A exists on some PAL systems; this is an RGB DAC, but RGB output is not populated in retail units.

---

## Bus Operation

The VI outputs video over a 7-bit synchronous bus (VDC_D0–D6) with VDC_DSYNC (!DSYNC). Data is multiplexed over four VI clock cycles per pixel:

* 1 pixel = 4 VI clocks
* 7 bits × 3 channels = 21-bit RGB

The Video DAC clock operates at **4× the pixel clock** (f_vi = 4 × f_pixel).

[[File:N64videosys.png|thumb|Video DAC Bus and waveform. Image from: [http://members.optusnet.com.au/eviltim/n64rgb/n64rgb.html](http://members.optusnet.com.au/eviltim/n64rgb/n64rgb.html)]]

The 4-cycle sequence carries both pixel data and control signals and restarts whenever !DSYNC is low.

The Video Interface transmits control signals continuously during blanking by holding !DSYNC low across multiple cycles.

